'''Domestic noir''' is a literary [[subgenre]] within [[crime fiction]]. Though used earlier in discussion of the [[film noir]] subgenre,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mardecortesbaja.com/2007/10/14/what-is-domestic-noir/|title=WHAT IS DOMESTIC NOIR?|date=14 October 2007|website=mardecortesbaja.com}}</ref> the term was applied to fiction in 2013 by the novelist [[Julia Crouch]], who has been described by the crime writer, [[Elizabeth Haynes (crime writer)|Elizabeth Haynes]], as "the queen of domestic noir".<ref name="Haynes">{{cite web|url=https://awaines.blogspot.com/2014/08/suburban-domestic-and-chick-noir-new.html|title=AJ Waines' Blog: Suburban, Domestic and Chick-Noir - New Genres in Psychological Thrillers|first=Aj|last=Waines|date=19 August 2014|website=awaines.blogspot.com}}</ref>  Crouch defined the subgenre in her blog:

{{quotation|In a nutshell, Domestic Noir takes place primarily in homes and workplaces, concerns itself largely (but not exclusively) with the female experience, is based around relationships and takes as its base a broadly feminist view that the [[Separate spheres|domestic sphere]] is a challenging and sometimes dangerous prospect for its inhabitants. That’s pretty much all of my work described there.<ref name="Genre Bender">[http://juliacrouch.co.uk/blog/genre-bender Julia Crouch, ‘Genre Bender’, Julia Crouch's blog, 25 August 2012],</ref>}}

Crouch's novels, ''Cuckoo'', ''The Long Fall'', ''Tarnished'' and ''Every Vow You Break'', had previously been categorized as [[psychological thriller]]s, a label she felt inadequate: 'The engine driving my work is more an unravelling than the high octane roller coaster suggested by the word 'thriller'.'<ref name="Genre Bender"/>

The term was embraced by fellow novelists, including Rebecca Whitney in an article in the [[Independent newspaper]],<ref name="Whitney">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/domestic-noir-is-bigger-than-ever-top-ten-releases-for-2015-9975488.html Rebecca Whitney, ''‘Domestic Noir is bigger than ever’'', The Independent, 13 January 2015]</ref> where she describes her own subject as 'the toxic marriage and its fall-out.' Whitney quotes Sophie Orme, Senior Editor at Mantle, on the appeal of Domestic Noir:

{{quotation|'Readers have a constant thirst for dark realism in novels; for books in which they can identify with the principal characters yet find themselves taken out of their day to day experiences. Marriage seems to me to be the ultimate setting to explore here – the culmination of a journey of love, a partnership, a relationship in which a couple places themselves in one another's hands entirely, where really the stakes could not be higher.’<ref name="Whitney"/>}}

Another crime novelist, A.J.Waines, describes domestic noir in her blog:

{{quotation|'The Family...is a cauldron for crime, bringing with it abductions, incarcerations, issues with infertility, infidelity and missing children. The home is rife with buried family secrets that come back to haunt us. This subgenre plays on the idea that the home is the safest place to be – OR IS IT..?' <ref name="Waines">{{cite web|url=https://awaines.blogspot.com/2014/08/suburban-domestic-and-chick-noir-new.html|title=AJ Waines' Blog: Suburban, Domestic and Chick-Noir - New Genres in Psychological Thrillers|first=Aj|last=Waines|date=19 August 2014|website=awaines.blogspot.com}}</ref>}}

The subgenre has also been labelled 'chick noir', though the novelist Luana Lewis has written that this term was 'viewed as offensive and degrading by many....The word “chick” inevitably implies female; or synonym for ‘not to be taken seriously'.'<ref name="Lewis">[http://londonwritersclub.com/2014/06/trends-in-crime-fiction-from-psychological-thrillers-to-domestic-noir/ Luana Lewis, London Writers' Club website, 27 June 2014],</ref>

Other women writing domestic noir include [[Erin Kelly (author)|Erin Kelly]], Araminta Hall, Paula Hawkins, [[Gillian Flynn]], [[Elizabeth Haynes (crime writer)|Elizabeth Haynes]], Sabine Durrant, Natalie Young, Louise Millar, [[Paula Daly]], Samantha Hayes, [[Louise Doughty]], [[Julie Myerson]], [[Jean Hanff Korelitz]], [[A. S. A. Harrison]] and [[Lionel Shriver]]. There are also male writers of the subgenre, such as S. J. Watson and Tom Vowler.

