'''''Sao Mi Zhou''''' ({{zh|t=掃迷帚|s=扫迷帚|p=sǎo mí zhǒu|l=The broom that sweeps away superstition}}) is a Chinese [[serial novel]] in 24 installments published in 1903 under the pseudonym Zhuàngzhě (壯者; lit. "strong man"). The word "superstition" ({{zh|c=迷信|p=míxìn}}) had just been introduced in the Chinese language (from [[Japanese language|Japanese]]) a few years earlier by [[Liang Qichao]].<ref>Goossaert, Vincent, and David Palmer, ''The Religious Question in Modern China'', Chicago: The University of Chicago Press, 2011</ref> The novel attempted to convince people to oppose traditional Chinese religious ideas, which the author saw as backward and an obstacle to progress. Most of the novel is built around a discussion on the topic between two brothers.

